==Portuguese==
===Etymology===
From Castillian '''[[ya]]''', from Latin '''[[iam]]'''.

===Adverb===
# [[already]]
# [[now]]
# [[anymore]]
# In the foreseeable future.

====Usage note====
"Já" means, generally, "at some point previous" or "since some point previous." In English, "already," the most common translation, is used only to emphasize that this point might have been expected to be later, whereas "now" is used to emphasize that the the statement was once false. "Já" is used to express either, although because it is shorter than "already," it is said more often and sometimes left untranslated altogether. (The most common Portuguese word for "now," "[[agora]]," means only the literal present moment.)  Also, where "já" means "now," it is often used in negative sentences, in which the most common English construction uses "anymore."  Also, with the future, the word often comes to mean simply "in the future."  This, too, is often left untranslated, or translated "soon."

